By the end of Week 23, the Democracy Clock stands at 7:56 p.m. The movement is modest in minutes, but large in what it represents. War powers have been asserted without effective oversight, and the tools available to courts to halt executive action have been narrowed. Immigration enforcement has become a proving ground for emergency governance, where masked agents, private contractors, and distant camps carry out policies that courts struggle to supervise. Public health, media, and universities\'97institutions that once mediated between power and the public\'97are being repopulated with loyalists or stripped of capacity. At the same time, judges, state officials, and local movements continue to resist, winning injunctions, exposing conflicts of interest, and electing new kinds of leaders.\
\
This week matters in the larger arc of the term because it shows how different domains\'97foreign war, domestic policing, courts, information, and representation\'97can be aligned around a single logic: concentrate authority, fragment oversight, and treat opposition as suspect. The Civic Covenant, as reflected in the moral floor, is cracked but not shattered. Courts still order deportees returned. Legislatures still debate war powers. Voters still elevate candidates who promise a different path. Yet the tools available to those actors are fewer than they were a week ago, and the costs of using them are higher. At 7:56 p.m., there is still daylight on the horizon, but the shadows of unchecked force and curated memory have grown longer.\
